          "End of Course",
          "The authors decide to do feature selection using the top-5 features for each year unsing the RF feature importances.\n\nTo do this, the authors rank the feature importances in each year and select the top-5 moist important ones.\n\nAuthors also subset their analysis across distinct demographiic segments:\n\n- English vs Non-English speakers\n- Citizens vs Non-Citizens",
          "Random Forest",
          "Holdout Method",
          "2015-2016 - NWF\n{Balanced Accuracy: 0.91 (current) vs 0.72 (subsequent)}\n\n2015-2016 - PBS\n{Balanced Accuracy: 0.86 (current) vs 0.72 (subsequent)}\n\n2016-2017 - NWF\n{Balanced Accuracy: 0.80 (current) vs 0.72 (subsequent)}\n\n2016-2017 - PBS\n{Balanced Accuracy: 0.78 (current) vs 0.71 (subsequent)}\n\n2017-2018 - NWF\n{Balanced Accuracy: 0.81 (current) vs 0.79 (subsequent)}\n\n2017-2018 - PBS\n{Balanced Accuracy: 0.79 (current) vs 0.78 (subsequent)}\n\n2018-2019 - NWF\n{Balanced Accuracy: 0.86 (current) vs 0.73 (subsequent)}\n\n2018-2019 - PBS\n{Balanced Accuracy: 0.83 (current) vs 0.74 (subsequent)}",
          "Most datassets in the real world are “not stationary”.  A fair algorithm trained at time t has no assurance of remaining fair at time t+1…\n\nThe authors m,ake an assessment of dataset drift in Learning Analytics student success models in 2 perspectives… how performance is affected from one academic year to next (it is…) and also how this is affected in terms of model fairness when comparing generral student populations (citizens orr english speakers vs other demographics).",
          "- Small number of courses in STEM.\n\n- Vulnerable to changes in instructional conditions from year to year.\n\n- Only tested on Randoom Forest\n\n- No early prediction"
        ]
